{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332893798/1930123101/0537.xml":{"full_text":"says W. E. HEANER:\nMGR. EAGLE PASS LUMBER CO.\n\u201cThe Eagle Pass Lumber Company Is very\noptimistic in its outlook for 1931. Such con\nstruction as the Filtration Plant few the City of\nBrownsville, the Grant Building, and numerous\nhomes has had its effect in the stimulating of\nbusiness for the coming year.\u201d\n\u2014W. E. HEANER.\nsays E. G. HOLLIDAY:\nBUILDER\n\u201cNineteen thirty has not been a bad year\nand the outlook for the coming year U very,\nvery bright. A great many construction Job*\nare in the process of making and if 50 per cent\ngo to fulfillment, the Valley will have known\nits greatest year.\u201d\n-E. G. HOLLIDAY\nsays TED NECK\u2022\nA. W. NECK SON\n\u201cBusiness looks good now and we have more\nprospects on the list than we have had any time\nin the past year.\u201d _\n\u2014TED NECK\nsays BEN V: PROCTOR\nPROCTOR DUDLEY\n\u201cThe business outlook in the Valley for the\ncoming year looks bright and it is bound to\npick up after the first of the month.\u201d\nEN V. PROCTOR\nsays GORDON STREET:\nRIO GRANDE VALLEY TRUST CO.\n\u2022\u2018Stocks of goods on hand are rapidly being\ndepleted which should mean a revival of buy\ning in the first three months of the year. The\nyears as a whole will be one of readjustment.\u201d\n\u2014GORDON STREET\nsays J. R. MATTHEWS:\nMATTHLV/S ELIAS\n\u201cVive year of 1930 has been one of those\nperi f when everythin-* possible has been put\noff. li nothing is done during the coming year\nbut to take care of those improvements that\nare necessary, it should be a very prosperous\nand busy year. Already our offices are figuring\nenough work to keep us busy for the first quar\nter of 1931\u201d\n-J. R. MATTHEWS\nsays E. P. ELLIS:\nELECTRICAL CONTRACTOR\n\u201cMy many years' experience throughout tha\ncountry has taught me never to be overly op\ntimistic, but the conditions faci: the Valley ar\u00ab\nso bright that even a pessimist is forced to ad\nmit that 1931 holds a promise for the most\nprosperous year in the history of the Valley.\u201d\n\u2014E. P. ELLIS\nsays H. RICHARDSON:\nBROWNSVILLE SHEET METAL WORKS\n\u201cAmong our many prosperous years In the\nValley and Brownsville, 1931 will stand out as a\ntriumphant year in its history. The Valley to\nday is working in unison. Its people are coop\nerating with a spirit of friendship that hereto\nfore has been unknown. The projects con\ntracted for or underway are far greater than any\nother period in our history. What more can\nbe asked for the assurance of a prosperous\nyear?\u201d\n\u2014H RICHARDSON.\nsays JOHN REZEK:\nORNAMENTAL IRON\n\u201cAlthough I have been in the Valley less\nthan a year. I have never been in business in\nany place where I found the spirit of coopera\ntion and feeling of good fellowship that exists\nhere. My business in the year 1930 increased\n35 per cent each month over the previous\nmonth. 1931 looks even brighter than 1390.\u201d\n\u2014JOHN REZEK.\nsays WILLIAM D.\nVAN SICLEN\nARCHITECT\n\u201cThe outlook for business for the coming\nyear is very bright, a number of people hav\u00bb\ndecided to build. Nothing will stop the tremen\ndous movement now on foot in the Valley.\u201d\n\u2014WILLIAM D. VAN SICLEN\nsays M. P. MULL:\nWELCH TILE MARBLE CO.\n\u2019When anyone asks us how business was In\nft30. we say okay.\u201d I am sure that without\nfalsifying in 1931 we can say \u201cBusiness Is fine!\u201d\n\u2014M. P. MULL\nsays N. R. QUINN:\nQUINN DERRICK\n\u201cIt is a>iOst impossible to measure In dol\nlars and cents the tremendous assets that 1930\nhas given Bro'vr.sviUe and the Valiev. With the\nassurance cf a Deep Water Port ai\u2019J the many\ncity and county improvements 1931 bids to be\nthe biggest year in the history cf our country.\u201d\n\u2014N. R. QUINN\nsays R. C. MORRIS:\nFRONTIER LUMBER CO.\nI \u201c'.Tort commodity prices have reached bot\nf tom, some are lower than they have been In\nyears. As soon as the general public recovers\nfrom the scare engendered by the stock crash,\nthey will avail themselves of these low prices\nand times will again be good. In fact, we can\nlook for the change before the middle of 1931.\nConditions will improve faster In the Valley\nthan elsewhere and we can confidently look\nforward to a marked improvement here within\nthe next three or four months.\"\n\u2014R. C. MORRIS.\n%l\nBROWNSVILLE\nOf Tomorrow\nf\n\nBrownsville will remain for the next decade, the\nbrightest spot in America. Its gains in the ranks of com\nmerce, finance, shipping, agriculture and industry during\nthe ten year period will be greater than any other city in\nthe nation. It will have a growing line of sh:ps that will\nreach out for a large volume of the world\u2019s trade. Its\nshops and factories will extend their sphere of usefulness\nf?~ther inland, even ints the Forty ei^ht 5'~* all of\nMexico.\nAs an integral part of the civic and commercial life\nof Brownsville, we are happy to have had part in placing\nit in the prominent position which it now holds. It has\nbeen a privilege, through the growth of our own invest\nment, and in the broadening of our scope of service, to\nhave been a part of the city\u2019s period of greatest progress*\nAnd now, as in the past, we are determined and pledge\nourselves to keep in step with its future growth.\n\nThis organization had its beginning in Brownsville*\nIt is conceived in the spirit of service to the home and in\ndustry. It is soundly organized and soundly financed\nby, of and for Brownsville people. It is now, as it\nhas been in the past, ably directed with an understanding\nsympathy for the best interests of her community\u2019s fu\nture.\nWe take this means of expressing our gratitude to\nthose thousands of friends and clients who have recog\nnized this spirit of service. As we enlarge our physical\nassets and widen our circle of usefulness, we shall con\ntinue in the future to keep abreast with the advance of\nBrownsville and the Valley and now, in giving you\nthat pledge, we salute Brownsville as the City of To\nmorrow.\n.The Brownsville Chapter of the National\nBuilders Construction Association\nsays LEE ADAMSON:\nFRONTIER LUMBER CO.\n\"Though the year 1930 has been In a ma\nterial way a disappointment to us, calm medi\ntation reveals that In times of adversity we\ncome to a better realization of trugu worth and\nreal values. This period of inactivity has been\n\u2022n opportunity for readjustment.\nTfcoee who are wise are taking advantage of\nlow prices, laying plans fer new expansion, and\nnew ventures, changing their business policies\nand otherwise \u2018putting their house in order.\u2019\n\"The knowledge that you are doing this and\nthat others are doing it. is within itself suffici\nent to give us a feeling of security and an op\ntimistic outlook for the coming year.\u2019\n-L. T. ADAMSON.\nsays D. L. WELCH:\nINSURANCE LOANS\n\u201cThe true spirit of optimism that counts Is\nonly shown by men and firms who really roll\nup their sleeves and work. The above state\nments arc by such people; they are of the type\nwho really make prosperity. Let us follow their\nexample and the future prosperity of the Val\nley will be assured.\u201d\nD. L. WELCH\nsays ED BOUNDS:\nEAGLE PASS LUMBER CO.\n\u201cI believe that the \u201cPaint Up and Clean\nUp\u201d Campaign has just now had its effect.\nSmall business is good and at a good time.\u201d\n\u2014ED. BOU2GD6.\nsays S. W. McKENZIE: ft\nBUILDER\n\"All Indications show that tfam will pw%\nup tn the coming year- The Na* flea Bs\u00abld\u00bb t\nIng la one aspect of prosperity far tha rut ora\nNineteen thirty-one iti was the pant year ter\nmembers of this association.} will be a banner\nyear for the Valley.\"\n_\u00ab w. M, icrMgta 1\nmm* waaaampav b\u00bb\nsays J. J. KEMMY: 1\nBARNES KEMMY\nTor year* Barm* and Kemmy kavo sstfb.\ned and been a part oJ the great a*\"**..' w,*\u00ab* ,-f\nthis Valley. At 